00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:36.910
And the analogy I like to
use is, say you have 10 cats,

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:39.110
and you want to know if
you're allergic to cats.

00:09:39.110 --> 00:09:41.330
So you get rid of
nine of your cats.

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:43.100
Do you feel better?

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:44.880
Maybe, but you still have a cat.

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:47.124
How are you supposed
to know whether or not

00:09:47.124 --> 00:09:49.290
cats impact you if you've
still got one hanging out?

00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:51.900
So you want to know if
you're allergic to cats.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:52.630
You have 10 cats.

00:09:52.630 --> 00:09:53.963
You give up all 10 of your cats.

00:09:53.963 --> 00:09:56.636
But Saturday morning, you kick
you heels up with the cat.

00:09:56.636 --> 00:09:58.010
Or Friday night,
you're like, I'm

00:09:58.010 --> 00:09:59.610
just going to have
one little cat.

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:00.460
Right?

00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:03.109
Whether that's pizza
or a beer or whatever

00:10:03.109 --> 00:10:05.150
it is you're thinking
about, you can't accurately

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:07.200
evaluate how these
foods are impacting you

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:09.900
if you're including them even
a little bit in the plan.

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:12.540
So it's 100%
elimination for 30 days.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:14.552
Think of it like a
scientific experiment.

00:10:14.552 --> 00:10:16.010
And if you do go
off-plan, I really

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:19.316
encourage people to start over,
both for the physiological

00:10:19.316 --> 00:10:20.690
reasons, but also,
because I want

00:10:20.690 --> 00:10:25.810
you to honor the commitment that
you made to yourself, 30 days.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:28.840
STACEY SASAKI: So you mentioned,
obviously, paleo in there.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:31.004
Is the Whole30 a paleo diet?

00:10:31.004 --> 00:10:31.920
Are there differences?

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:32.420
What's the--

00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:34.545
MELISSA HARTWIG: There are
significant differences.

00:10:34.545 --> 00:10:36.920
It's based on the general
framework of the paleo diet

00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:38.880
because the research
behind the foods that

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:41.230
are eliminated on the paleo
diet are pretty solid.

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:43.960
Again, we're not saying
these foods are good or bad.

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.501
We're not saying these foods
are healthy or less healthy

00:10:46.501 --> 00:10:47.000
for you.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.880
We're saying they're
very commonly

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.620
problematic to varying degrees.

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:53.000
And I don't know how they
work for you until you

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.590
do the Whole30 and
do this experiment

00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:57.390
and figure it out for yourself.

00:10:57.390 --> 00:11:01.170
So the foods that you eliminate
on the Whole30 like grains,

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:03.220
legumes, and dairy
are all foods that

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:05.650
are also off-limits with
the paleo-style diet.

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:07.999
But we do include
potatoes in the Whole30

00:11:07.999 --> 00:11:09.790
because they're a real
nutrient-dense food.

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:12.320
And lots of paleo people
say potatoes don't count.

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:14.290
You're not allowed to
do those egg and banana

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:16.695
pancakes that I talked
about and some of the paleo

00:11:16.695 --> 00:11:18.320
treats and desserts
that are out there.

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:19.570
So there are some differences.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:23.530
Our program is for a
very specific purpose.

00:11:23.530 --> 00:11:25.840
STACEY SASAKI: And so
when we're talking about,

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.400
we do this Whole30.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:28.100
We make it.

00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:29.310
Thank, god.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:30.800
What happens next?

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:31.345
It's scary.

00:11:31.345 --> 00:11:32.720
MELISSA HARTWIG:
It can be scary.

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:34.560
And that's really what "Food
Freedom Forever" is about

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:35.250
is people did the Whole30.

00:11:35.250 --> 00:11:36.708
We've had millions
of people do it.

00:11:36.708 --> 00:11:37.970
And they have amazing success.

00:11:37.970 --> 00:11:40.060
And they feel like they
really changed their habits.

00:11:40.060 --> 00:11:42.560
And it's like the first thing
that's really worked for them.

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:44.080
And then they're
like, OK, now what?

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:46.621
Because I don't want to go back
to the way that I was eating,

00:11:46.621 --> 00:11:48.400
but I don't know
how to not do that,

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:50.240
especially in the
face of a holiday,

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:52.550
a vacation, a stressful event.

00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:54.830
So that's really what
"Food Freedom Forever"

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:56.610
is about is it's
the three-step plan

00:11:56.610 --> 00:12:00.490
to help people get past that
short-term dietary intervention

00:12:00.490 --> 00:12:03.240
and turn what they've
learned into a lifetime

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:04.440
of healthy habits.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:06.760
STACEY SASAKI: So it
stems from the terror

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:08.590
that people feel
when they're like,

00:12:08.590 --> 00:12:10.336
oh, I have to go back
into the real world

00:12:10.336 --> 00:12:11.459
now, eat some real food.

00:12:11.459 --> 00:12:12.750
What's that going to look like?

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:14.083
I mean, maybe that's excitement.

00:12:14.083 --> 00:12:16.337
But I think for a lot of
people, it's also terror.

00:12:16.337 --> 00:12:17.920
MELISSA HARTWIG: We
call it frexcited.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:19.910
It's frightened and
excited at the same time.

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:20.130
Right?

00:12:20.130 --> 00:12:22.380
I mean, you're excited to
get back to some of the foods

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:24.100
that you really love and
see how they work for you.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:26.390
But at the same time, you
feel so good that you just

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:27.431
don't want to mess it up.

00:12:27.431 --> 00:12:30.180
And you're afraid that if you
do let some of these foods

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:32.880
back in, it's going to send
you down this slippery slide

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:35.937
of feeling out of control again.

00:12:35.937 --> 00:12:38.270
And I've provided a lot of
guidance over the years about

00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:41.640
what to do, but never in a
really clear step-by- step

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:42.890
do this, do that format.

00:12:42.890 --> 00:12:46.310
So this came from my community
saying, I need more help.

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:48.934
I need more help in
life after the Whole30.

00:12:48.934 --> 00:12:50.850
STACEY SASAKI: You
mentioned that carbopalooza

00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:53.210
that could happen immediately
following your Whole30.

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:56.400
Day 31, yay, I can
have all the pasta.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:58.250
But I don't think
that's how it works.

00:12:58.250 --> 00:12:59.750
So tell us about
the reintroduction.

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:01.374
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Yeah, we did a survey.

00:13:01.374 --> 00:13:03.750
I think we had more than
5,000 Whole30ers respond.

00:13:03.750 --> 00:13:05.561
And of those people
who finished a Whole30

00:13:05.561 --> 00:13:07.560
and said that at the
beginning of their program,

00:13:07.560 --> 00:13:09.060
they thought they
were going to want

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:12.067
to eat all the things on Day
31, 75% of them at the end

00:13:12.067 --> 00:13:13.400
said, I actually didn't want to.

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:14.357
I felt so different.

00:13:14.357 --> 00:13:16.690
And things had changed so
much-- my tastes had changed--

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:18.670
that I didn't want to do that.

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:22.180
But in between the
Whole30 and your food

00:13:22.180 --> 00:13:24.530
freedom comes this
reintroduction period.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:27.120
Remember, you eliminate, and
then you bring them back in.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:31.060
So we've got both a 10-day
fast track reintroduction

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:32.710
outlined in the "Whole30" book.

00:13:32.710 --> 00:13:34.865
And then we've got
this slow roll option

00:13:34.865 --> 00:13:36.990
for people who maybe don't
want to bring everything

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:38.480
back in within 10 days.

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:41.130
But the reintroduction is
the money of the program.

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.160
This is where you learn
how these foods impact you

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:47.120
and where you learn
how much and how often

00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:49.660
and what kinds of foods you
can bring back into your life

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:52.140
so that it's delicious and
healthy and feels sustainable,

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:54.190
but in a way that's not
going to mess you up

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:56.938
in terms of how awesome
you want to look and feel.

00:13:56.938 --> 00:13:58.240
STACEY SASAKI: Great.

00:13:58.240 --> 00:14:02.280
So if we're slowly reintroducing
things, what does it look like?

00:14:02.280 --> 00:14:04.850
Say, OK, today is dairy day.

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:08.590
Do I go and eat yogurt
all day and top if off

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:10.955
with a dab of milk and
then have a brick of cheese

00:14:10.955 --> 00:14:11.580
with ice cream?

00:14:11.580 --> 00:14:12.500
MELISSA HARTWIG: Maybe
not a brick of cheese.

00:14:12.500 --> 00:14:12.680
STACEY SASAKI: No?

00:14:12.680 --> 00:14:13.432
Oh, OK.

00:14:13.432 --> 00:14:15.190
MELISSA HARTWIG: But basically,
what you want to do-- again,

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:16.898
think of it like a
scientific experiment.

00:14:16.898 --> 00:14:18.870
Dairy is going to be
your experimental factor.

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:20.203
And the Whole30 is your control.

00:14:20.203 --> 00:14:21.930
So your entire diet
for the whole day

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:23.230
is going to be Whole30.

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:25.670
The only thing you're
adding back in is dairy.

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:27.680
So you would do your
typical Whole30 breakfast.

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:31.830
Maybe it's some poached eggs,
maybe a little bit of avocado

00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:34.070
and a veggie medley
and some mixed berries.

00:14:34.070 --> 00:14:36.459
But you're going to sprinkle
some cheese on your eggs.

00:14:36.459 --> 00:14:38.000
So you're going to
add the dairy back

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.470
in a way that allows you
to evaluate just the dairy

00:14:41.470 --> 00:14:42.220
component alone.

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:44.886
And then you're going to go back
to the Whole30 for two or three

00:14:44.886 --> 00:14:47.006
days and see what happens
in terms of the reaction

00:14:47.006 --> 00:14:48.880
because sometimes the
reaction can take a day

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:51.150
or so to manifest, depending
on how sensitive you are.

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:53.600
STACEY SASAKI: You don't
want to overdo it, but slowly

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:54.490
bring it in and test it out.

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:56.200
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah, and
you have to do enough of it

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:56.830
to really see.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:59.030
So if you just put a drop
of milk in your coffee,

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:00.410
what are the chances
that you're really

00:15:00.410 --> 00:15:01.320
going to notice an impact?

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:03.240
So you want to do some
cream in your coffee,

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:05.640
some cheese on your omelet,
maybe a side of yogurt

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:08.041
with your lunch, and then
at dinner, some other form

00:15:08.041 --> 00:15:09.290
of dairy that you really like.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:12.110
What you don't want to
do is do a giant bowl

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:14.440
of ice cream that also has
cookie dough, that also

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:16.460
is topped with chocolate syrup
because then you're not going

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:18.780
to know what's impacting
you, the dairy or the gluten

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:21.380
or the massive sugar bomb.

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:22.130
STACEY SASAKI: OK.

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:24.650
So what about people
who-- is there

00:15:24.650 --> 00:15:28.656
some way to do this if you
don't want to go strict Whole30?

00:15:28.656 --> 00:15:30.030
They're pretty
strict guidelines.

00:15:30.030 --> 00:15:31.570
I think that they
make a lot of fans.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:32.986
And it's really
great to find out.

00:15:32.986 --> 00:15:36.425
But some people are like, so
if I said I want to do this,

00:15:36.425 --> 00:15:39.770
but I don't care how
alcohol affects me.

00:15:39.770 --> 00:15:41.410
I don't care if it
makes me bloated.

00:15:41.410 --> 00:15:43.240
I don't care if it
makes my skin break out.

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:44.930
I want to try to get rid
of all the other things,

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:45.680
bring it all in.

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:48.755
Can I still do a
Whole30ish program?

00:15:48.755 --> 00:15:50.284
Or is it a no-no?

00:15:50.284 --> 00:15:51.700
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Doing the Whole30

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:53.100
is a little like being pregnant.

00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:54.480
You either are, or you're not.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:56.540
There is no kind of, right?

00:15:56.540 --> 00:15:58.710
So if you're going
to do the program,

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:00.260
the way I describe
it is if you're

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:02.870
going to come play my game,
you need to play by my rules.

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:04.597
And all I'm asking
for is 30 days.

00:16:04.597 --> 00:16:06.930
And all I'm asking is for you
to trust me for one month.

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:09.580
And I've got seven years
of experience backing up

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:10.600
my recommendations.

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:12.970
But the Whole30 is
not for everyone.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:14.750
So if you're vegan,
for example, you

00:16:14.750 --> 00:16:17.320
can't do the Whole30 as written
because we are basically

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:20.080
excluding all of your
plant-based protein sources.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:21.790
And the rules are rigid.

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:23.890
And it's a lot to imagine
giving up at once.

00:16:23.890 --> 00:16:27.100
It can be a very
emotional journey.

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:28.790
So in "Food Freedom
Forever," I have

00:16:28.790 --> 00:16:31.530
outlined several different
resets that you can do,

00:16:31.530 --> 00:16:33.980
not all of which are as
intense as the Whole30,

00:16:33.980 --> 00:16:35.730
but all of which will
get you to the place

00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:37.512
where you know how
food impacts you,

00:16:37.512 --> 00:16:39.970
and you're in a better balance
in terms of your blood sugar

00:16:39.970 --> 00:16:42.650
regulation, hormonal balance,
digestion, and immune system.

00:16:42.650 --> 00:16:45.450
So the Whole30 isn't
the price of admission

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:47.154
for "Food "Freedom,"
but I will strongly

00:16:47.154 --> 00:16:48.320
encourage everyone to do it.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:50.406
And I do several
times in the book.

00:16:50.406 --> 00:16:51.364
STACEY SASAKI: Awesome.

00:16:51.364 --> 00:16:54.360
So if you're looking
to do something,

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:57.150
your book will give you a few
different options for things.

00:16:57.150 --> 00:16:59.200
Yeah, I did have the
question as well is,

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:02.320
if I'm a vegetarian,
vegan, or I can't have soy,

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:04.840
so I can't have tofu,
which I would usually

00:17:04.840 --> 00:17:06.720
have on the Whole30 strictly.

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:08.510
But you definitely
give people options.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:10.489
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah,
there is a full vegan

00:17:10.489 --> 00:17:11.569
reset outlined here.

00:17:11.569 --> 00:17:15.400
And you're eliminating the most
commonly problematic protein

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:17.750
sources, again, according
to the literature.

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:20.240
And in all of the resets,
you're pulling out alcohol.

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:21.325
Like, come on, guys.

00:17:21.325 --> 00:17:23.200
You're going to pull
out alcohol for 30 days.

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:23.700
Right?

00:17:23.700 --> 00:17:25.866
In all of the resets, you're
eliminating added sugar

00:17:25.866 --> 00:17:28.010
and some of those processed
food with no breaks,

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:31.460
and some of those sweet treats
and desserts and baked goods.

00:17:31.460 --> 00:17:34.850
All of the resets,
that's the very baseline

00:17:34.850 --> 00:17:35.720
of the elimination.

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:37.740
There's a basic reset
outlined in here

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:39.580
that's as bare
bones as possible.

00:17:39.580 --> 00:17:42.845
But what I say in the book,
with all sorts of tough love--

00:17:42.845 --> 00:17:44.470
emphasis on the love--
is if you're not

00:17:44.470 --> 00:17:46.270
willing to do at
least this, you're

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:47.812
not ready for this
program right now.

00:17:47.812 --> 00:17:48.936
STACEY SASAKI: That's fair.

00:17:48.936 --> 00:17:49.550
That's fair.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:51.000
I like the tough
love in the book.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:52.618
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Heavy on the love.

00:17:52.618 --> 00:17:54.390
STACEY SASAKI: Yes,
of course, of course.

00:17:54.390 --> 00:17:55.305
But it's very real.

00:17:55.305 --> 00:17:57.170
You give it us straight.

00:17:57.170 --> 00:17:59.250
So I very much appreciate that.

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:01.660
Have you ever had anybody go
through the Whole30 program

00:18:01.660 --> 00:18:03.330
and do their whole
reintroduction, ad

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:06.060
they're just like, I don't
notice anything different.

00:18:06.060 --> 00:18:09.640
I don't notice any of my
allergies flare up or whatever.

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:11.194
I still had headaches
the whole time.

00:18:11.194 --> 00:18:12.360
Is there anything like that?

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:13.943
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Sometimes the Whole30

00:18:13.943 --> 00:18:16.830
doesn't work super well
for absolutely everybody.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:20.470
For some people, food may
not be your biggest issue.

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:23.170
If you've already been eating
really squeaky clean or close

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:26.487
to Whole30ish and you're
already pretty healthy,

00:18:26.487 --> 00:18:28.070
maybe there's something
else going on.

00:18:28.070 --> 00:18:30.528
Maybe it's because you're only
sleeping five hours a night,

00:18:30.528 --> 00:18:32.670
or you're doing two-a-day
CrossFit sessions

00:18:32.670 --> 00:18:34.100
and not recovering actively.

00:18:34.100 --> 00:18:36.500
So food might not be
your biggest issue.

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:38.520
The Whole30 also
can't fix everything.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:41.520
So if you've got this
underlying, undiagnosed gut

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:43.580
infection or you've got
an autoimmune condition

00:18:43.580 --> 00:18:45.830
that you've been living with
and it's been progressing

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:47.655
for the last 20
years, the Whole30

00:18:47.655 --> 00:18:49.780
might give you a good start
towards feeling better.

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:51.960
But you may need to work with
a functional medicine doctor

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:54.390
to make sure that you're
getting the treatment that's

00:18:54.390 --> 00:18:56.290
applicable for you.

00:18:56.290 --> 00:18:57.140
Yeah.

00:18:57.140 --> 00:18:59.850
STACEY SASAKI: So yeah,
that makes a lot of sense.

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:02.430
The other thing that I
think can be problematic

00:19:02.430 --> 00:19:06.900
is the whole thing around
social networks, family.

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:08.170
How do you navigate that?

00:19:08.170 --> 00:19:09.910
I know going to my
mom's and saying,

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:11.368
oh, I'm not eating
gluten or dairy.

00:19:11.368 --> 00:19:12.372
I'm not having alcohol.

00:19:12.372 --> 00:19:14.580
I'm not-- she'll just be
like, well, don't come home.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:16.250
MELISSA HARTWIG: Right.

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:17.610
STACEY SASAKI: So what do we do?

00:19:17.610 --> 00:19:19.810
MELISSA HARTWIG: So
not what you just said.

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:20.050
STACEY SASAKI: OK.

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:21.370
MELISSA HARTWIG: That's
a terrible way to do it.

00:19:21.370 --> 00:19:23.965
I actually have three chapters
in "Food Freedom Forever"

00:19:23.965 --> 00:19:26.090
about how to talk to friends,
family, and coworkers

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:27.840
about food, three chapters.

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:30.740
Not overkill because talking to
friends and family about food

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:33.160
is third only to
religion and politics

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:34.770
in terms of how
divisive it can be.

00:19:34.770 --> 00:19:37.520
You started talking about
food and changing your diet,

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:39.180
and immediately,
people get judgmental.

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:41.717
They get defensive like you
don't have to do anything.

00:19:41.717 --> 00:19:44.050
You can just roll up to the
table with your Whole30 meal

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:45.590
and the entire table
all of a sudden

00:19:45.590 --> 00:19:47.380
feels like it's being attacked.

00:19:47.380 --> 00:19:50.390
So what I like to
say is A, don't have

00:19:50.390 --> 00:19:52.380
the conversation over food.

00:19:52.380 --> 00:19:52.880
Right?

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:55.620
Have it away from food and
ideally, ahead of time.

00:19:55.620 --> 00:19:57.530
B, you always want
to be lead with all

00:19:57.530 --> 00:19:59.050
of the positive things.

00:19:59.050 --> 00:20:02.180
And you want to make the
conversation as personal

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:04.410
as is appropriate for
your relationship.

00:20:04.410 --> 00:20:06.640
So if you're talking to
your mom, and you say,

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:08.654
I hear the Whole30 is
really good for cravings,

00:20:08.654 --> 00:20:11.070
that's not going to particularly
bring you close together.

00:20:11.070 --> 00:20:13.590
If you say, Mom, you sent me
home with your chocolate chip

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:14.665
cookies the other day.

00:20:14.665 --> 00:20:16.290
And I said I was only
going to eat one.

00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:17.520
And I ended up eating five.

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:19.560
And it makes me feel
really bad about myself

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:21.520
that I can't control
what I'm eating.

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:23.700
So I'm going to do this
experiment for 30 days

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:26.050
where I try to break
my reliance on sugar

00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:27.410
and change my cravings.

00:20:27.410 --> 00:20:29.440
It means I won't be able
to eat your cookies.

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:30.710
But it's only for a month.

00:20:30.710 --> 00:20:33.010
And when I get done, I'll
be able to really enjoy

00:20:33.010 --> 00:20:34.690
them the way you want me to.

00:20:34.690 --> 00:20:35.240
Right?

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:38.000
That's a totally
different conversation.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:39.240
So make it personal.

00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:40.590
And then make it relatable.

00:20:40.590 --> 00:20:42.290
So if your mom is
mostly sedentary,

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:43.914
you saying, I'm going
to do the Whole30

00:20:43.914 --> 00:20:46.820
and I'm hoping to cut my
5K time by three minutes,

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:47.520
not relatable.

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:49.340
If you know your
mom also suffers

00:20:49.340 --> 00:20:53.220
from cravings or sleep or
energy issues, bond with her

00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:53.807
on that level.

00:20:53.807 --> 00:20:55.890
Man, every day at 2 o'clock,
my head's on my desk,

00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:57.886
and I feel like I need
caffeine and chocolate.

00:20:57.886 --> 00:20:58.760
You know what I mean?

00:20:58.760 --> 00:20:59.760
Oh, yeah, me too.

00:20:59.760 --> 00:21:02.140
I'm going to do this
Whole30 because it's really

00:21:02.140 --> 00:21:04.120
meant to reset
your energy levels

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:07.570
and give you that awake feeling
without needing extra caffeine.

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:09.780
And now, she's listening.

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:10.864
So those are my best tips.

00:21:10.864 --> 00:21:12.613
STACEY SASAKI: Is that
where you also say,

00:21:12.613 --> 00:21:13.970
maybe you should do it with me?

00:21:13.970 --> 00:21:14.954
Or how does that work?

00:21:14.954 --> 00:21:17.370
MELISSA HARTWIG: Tread very
carefully with that, you guys.

00:21:17.370 --> 00:21:20.310
The phrase I like to use
is lead by quiet example.

00:21:20.310 --> 00:21:22.000
You can ask for her support.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.502
Mom, will you
support me in this?

00:21:23.502 --> 00:21:25.210
If I'm having a tough
day, can I call you

00:21:25.210 --> 00:21:27.150
and have you tell me what
a good job I'm doing?

00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:29.691
But you don't want to ever push
someone into trying to do it.

00:21:29.691 --> 00:21:30.230
Right?

00:21:30.230 --> 00:21:31.990
Instead, just lead
by quiet example.

00:21:31.990 --> 00:21:32.980
Look awesome.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:33.830
Feel awesome.

00:21:33.830 --> 00:21:36.710
Talk about your results,
your non-scale victories.

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:39.597
Hey, Mom, I saw a plate of
cookies at the office today,

00:21:39.597 --> 00:21:40.680
and I wasn't even tempted.

00:21:40.680 --> 00:21:41.530
I feel so good.

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:44.050
What a great sign that is.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:46.600
And then just sit back
because at some point,

00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:48.989
they will say, what
have you been doing.

00:21:48.989 --> 00:21:50.280
Tell me a little more about it.

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:52.321
And maybe it will take
them a while to get there,

00:21:52.321 --> 00:21:54.549
but you just do you.

00:21:54.549 --> 00:21:56.340
STACEY SASAKI: Talk to
me a little bit more

00:21:56.340 --> 00:21:58.310
about non-scale
victories because I

00:21:58.310 --> 00:22:01.680
think our society is really
obsessed with that number that

00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:03.630
appears whenever you get on it.

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:04.880
How do you get away from that?

00:22:04.880 --> 00:22:06.570
What are the things
to celebrate?

00:22:06.570 --> 00:22:07.820
I think that's a good example.

00:22:07.820 --> 00:22:08.950
Walking away from the
cookies, I think, Is huge.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:09.700
MELISSA HARTWIG: It's huge.

00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:11.550
And so one of the
other rules of the 30

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:12.966
is that you're not
allowed to step

00:22:12.966 --> 00:22:15.580
on the scale for 30 days,
which, for some, is the hardest

00:22:15.580 --> 00:22:16.980
rule of them all.

00:22:16.980 --> 00:22:18.510
But it is not a
weight loss program.

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:21.370
And it is not about weight.

00:22:21.370 --> 00:22:23.330
I think we all need
a break from letting

00:22:23.330 --> 00:22:25.970
this $20 hunk of plastic
hold our self-esteem

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:27.600
and self-confidence hostage.

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:30.360
So we focus on what we
call non-scale victories.

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:32.880
And in Whole30 lingo,
it's hashtag #NSV.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:34.900
And what people will
do is look for things

00:22:34.900 --> 00:22:37.100
like-- maybe some of
them are physical.

00:22:37.100 --> 00:22:39.160
Maybe it's oh, I'm
down about belt loop.

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:41.100
Or my wedding ring now fits.

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:42.680
It was too small,
and now it fits.

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:44.150
I love hearing that.

00:22:44.150 --> 00:22:47.552
Maybe it's a craving thing,
like I didn't need the cookie.

00:22:47.552 --> 00:22:49.010
I was able to walk
past the cookie.

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:50.950
Or I didn't need the candy bar.

00:22:50.950 --> 00:22:53.030
Or I finally feel like
I'm in control of food.

00:22:53.030 --> 00:22:54.400
Maybe it's digestive.

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:56.460
Maybe it's skin glowing
and clearing up.

00:22:56.460 --> 00:22:57.850
We hear a lot of that.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:00.290
Maybe it's I went to my
doctor and my blood sugar

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:01.460
is better managed.

00:23:01.460 --> 00:23:03.130
Or I'm no longer
type 2 diabetic.

00:23:03.130 --> 00:23:06.456
But there is this huge list
of non-scale victory in a PDF

00:23:06.456 --> 00:23:07.830
we give you on
the Whole30 sheet.

00:23:07.830 --> 00:23:09.090
And it's like, check
them off, people,

00:23:09.090 --> 00:23:11.270
because the more you can
check off, the more motivated

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:12.269
you will be to continue.

00:23:12.269 --> 00:23:13.510
STACEY SASAKI: Totally.

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:16.440
And so even after the
Whole30, is it still no scale?

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:19.172
Are you anti-scale?

00:23:19.172 --> 00:23:21.650
MELISSA HARTWIG: I'm anti-scale
if getting on that number

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:23.060
actually matters.

00:23:23.060 --> 00:23:25.162
If you with trepidation
close your eyes

00:23:25.162 --> 00:23:27.370
and cross your fingers before
you step on that scale,

00:23:27.370 --> 00:23:29.356
maybe it's better to
get off the scale.

00:23:29.356 --> 00:23:30.480
I have a scale at my house.

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:34.910
I use it to weigh my suitcases--
68 pounds for this trip, 68--

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:35.883
or to weight my son.

00:23:35.883 --> 00:23:38.007
And occasionally, I'll step
on and just kind of see

00:23:38.007 --> 00:23:38.507
where I am.

00:23:38.507 --> 00:23:40.600
But it doesn't mean anything.

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:42.530
So I am OK with
weighing yourself

00:23:42.530 --> 00:23:44.982
before and after because
for some people, obviously,

00:23:44.982 --> 00:23:47.440
I understand weight loss is a
big goal for a lot of people.

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:49.540
And I don't want to
minimize how amazing it

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:52.850
is if you can eat to satiety
and not count calories and still

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:53.585
lose weight.

00:23:53.585 --> 00:23:54.510
Awesome.

00:23:54.510 --> 00:23:59.480
But if that number is going to
ruin your day or make your day,

00:23:59.480 --> 00:24:02.130
maybe you should examine your
relationship with the scale.

00:24:02.130 --> 00:24:03.296
STACEY SASAKI: Totally fair.

00:24:03.296 --> 00:24:04.080
Totally fair.

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:07.500
In terms of either
technologies-- we're Google.

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:10.540
We care about are there things
that you are on board with?

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:13.490
Again, things that are
helpful, [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:13.490 --> 00:24:18.937
fitness trackers, wearables,
the posture coach, the fork

00:24:18.937 --> 00:24:20.270
that you mentioned in your book.

00:24:20.270 --> 00:24:21.120
MELISSA HARTWIG: The happy fork.

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:23.085
Yeah, I don't know
about the happy fork.

00:24:23.085 --> 00:24:26.930
It vibrates to let you know
if you're eating too quickly.

00:24:26.930 --> 00:24:27.910
But it's like 80 bucks.

00:24:27.910 --> 00:24:29.284
So I'm like, maybe
you could just

00:24:29.284 --> 00:24:31.360
stop eating like
you're in prison.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:32.473
STACEY SASAKI: That's one
of my favorite quotes.

00:24:32.473 --> 00:24:33.900
MELISSA HARTWIG: But i
do like the wearables.

00:24:33.900 --> 00:24:35.774
If you're the kind of
person who is motivated

00:24:35.774 --> 00:24:38.470
by seeing your
results, then things

00:24:38.470 --> 00:24:40.760
that can improve on the
Whole30 that you'll notice

00:24:40.760 --> 00:24:43.624
is naturally, your steps will go
up because you'll feel better,

00:24:43.624 --> 00:24:45.040
and you'll want
to be more active,

00:24:45.040 --> 00:24:46.120
and you'll park further away.

00:24:46.120 --> 00:24:47.703
And you won't sweat
taking the stairs.

00:24:47.703 --> 00:24:48.380
So that's cool.

00:24:48.380 --> 00:24:50.602
Your sleep quality, being
able to track your sleep,

00:24:50.602 --> 00:24:52.310
and whether you're
falling asleep easier,

00:24:52.310 --> 00:24:54.640
sleeping longer, getting
more restful sleep,

00:24:54.640 --> 00:24:56.640
awesome non-scale
victory on the Whole30.

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:59.460
So if you can find some
of those little ways

00:24:59.460 --> 00:25:02.900
to not only track your
progress, but tie it to wow,

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:05.490
it's stuff that you wouldn't
necessarily, I guess,

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:06.990
link back to your diet.

00:25:06.990 --> 00:25:08.450
Taking more steps?

00:25:08.450 --> 00:25:11.402
But if you see a change in that,
it can be really motivating.

00:25:11.402 --> 00:25:12.699
STACEY SASAKI: Yeah.

00:25:12.699 --> 00:25:14.740
I have one last question
for you before I open it

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:17.340
up to everybody, who's probably
dying to ask you things.

00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:18.750
They're like, stop talking.

00:25:18.750 --> 00:25:21.990
But I'm curious about just
changing the whole relationship

00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:23.870
about good and bad foods.

00:25:23.870 --> 00:25:26.660
And how do you even
get to that thought

00:25:26.660 --> 00:25:27.940
because I think it's hard.

00:25:27.940 --> 00:25:31.350
It's very hard for people to
know that it's not necessarily

00:25:31.350 --> 00:25:33.150
this is good for you,
this is bad for you,

00:25:33.150 --> 00:25:35.290
or you're a good
person or a bad person.

00:25:35.290 --> 00:25:37.850
And you talk a lot about
the language of food.

00:25:37.850 --> 00:25:39.080
How do we change that?

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:40.705
MELISSA HARTWIG: It's
really important.

00:25:40.705 --> 00:25:42.260
I think the language
of food is often

00:25:42.260 --> 00:25:44.490
what's holding us hostage
in our relationship.

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:47.102
And what I really
emphasize in the Whole30

00:25:47.102 --> 00:25:49.310
and also in "Food Freedom"
is these foods that you're

00:25:49.310 --> 00:25:52.290
eliminating, it's not
because they're bad.

00:25:52.290 --> 00:25:53.976
There's no good or bad food.

00:25:53.976 --> 00:25:55.850
You're pulling them out
and putting them back

00:25:55.850 --> 00:25:57.131
in because they're unknown.

00:25:57.131 --> 00:25:57.630
That's it.

00:25:57.630 --> 00:25:59.713
You just want to figure
out how they work for you.

00:25:59.713 --> 00:26:02.040
And you are not good or
bad based on the food

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:03.590
that you put on your plate.

00:26:03.590 --> 00:26:08.480
And I think once we can get
past the idea of our self-worth

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:11.440
being tied to what
our body weight is,

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:14.310
or what size jeans we
fit into, or whether we

00:26:14.310 --> 00:26:17.630
are the exerciser or
the healthy person,

00:26:17.630 --> 00:26:19.190
I think it makes
a huge difference

00:26:19.190 --> 00:26:22.760
in letting food be
more fun and easy

00:26:22.760 --> 00:26:25.260
and playful and
rewarding and joyful.

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:27.640
I'm not trying to
take any of that away.

00:26:27.640 --> 00:26:30.690
So I write a lot about the
idea of a growth mindset

00:26:30.690 --> 00:26:32.990
and changing your language.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:38.210
It's a real shift, a re-frame,
from the diet culture

00:26:38.210 --> 00:26:40.120
we've had for the
last 20 years, where

00:26:40.120 --> 00:26:44.040
it was all about deprivation
and restriction and willpower

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:46.070
and good foods and bad foods.

00:26:46.070 --> 00:26:49.195
And I want to change
all of that paradigm.

00:26:49.195 --> 00:26:51.070
STACEY SASAKI: The
learning to think about it

00:26:51.070 --> 00:26:54.180
in a different way than we
do, it just seems so hard.

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:57.266
But I think that you give a
lot of great tips in the book.

00:26:57.266 --> 00:26:58.484
I won't spoil them all.

00:26:58.484 --> 00:27:01.170
But yeah, I think
it's a challenge

00:27:01.170 --> 00:27:04.409
to be solved, related to
the goods and the bads.

00:27:04.409 --> 00:27:06.700
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah, but
the more you practice that--

00:27:06.700 --> 00:27:09.180
and I talk about things
like leaving post-it notes

00:27:09.180 --> 00:27:10.030
around your house.

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:12.130
It sounds kind of
silly, but the more

00:27:12.130 --> 00:27:14.490
you can reinforce
the ideas behind,

00:27:14.490 --> 00:27:17.370
I'm a healthy person
with healthy habits.

00:27:17.370 --> 00:27:19.060
And I'm living a
healthy lifestyle.

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:21.670
And this is a
scientific experiment.

00:27:21.670 --> 00:27:22.710
It's an experiment.

00:27:22.710 --> 00:27:23.730
It's not a diet.

00:27:23.730 --> 00:27:27.630
And the more you can re-frame--
and I really emphasize that

00:27:27.630 --> 00:27:30.190
over and over again-- I
think the better chance

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:32.010
you have of that
actually sticking.

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:34.440
And changing your foods and
changing your relationship

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:35.430
with foods and
feeling like you're

00:27:35.430 --> 00:27:38.103
building new healthy habits will
only serve to reinforce that.

00:27:38.103 --> 00:27:39.430
STACEY SASAKI: I love that.

00:27:39.430 --> 00:27:40.070
That's great.

