00:28:00.277 --> 00:28:02.610
I was wondering if you could
elaborate a little bit more

00:28:02.610 --> 00:28:05.080
on your last point there,
about the idea of after you're

00:28:05.080 --> 00:28:08.700
done with the
Whole30, not thinking

00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:11.274
about foods as good and bad.

00:28:11.274 --> 00:28:12.940
I don't know too much
about the Whole30.

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.320
But I've seen peers or
people on my Facebook

00:28:16.320 --> 00:28:17.700
or whatever doing it.

00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:19.810
And to me, it always
kind of worries me,

00:28:19.810 --> 00:28:24.690
the idea of saying you
can't have these things.

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:27.850
And it seems a little bit sad
if after the Whole30 would end,

00:28:27.850 --> 00:28:30.390
then you still feel like,
I can't have the cookies.

00:28:30.390 --> 00:28:32.390
I can't have--
even if you end up

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:36.550
being OK with dairy and eggs.

00:28:36.550 --> 00:28:39.980
And eating disorders are also
a thing that happens too.

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:42.897
So, I guess, what's your
perspective on after people

00:28:42.897 --> 00:28:44.480
finish the Whole30
and they figure out

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:47.840
what they can and can't have,
then transitioning to be like,

00:28:47.840 --> 00:28:49.857
OK, now we're going to
bake pumpkin cookies.

00:28:49.857 --> 00:28:50.940
And I'm going to have one.

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:51.600
And that's OK.

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:53.849
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah, that's
a really great question.

00:28:53.849 --> 00:28:57.261
And that all-or-nothing
is the diet mentality.

00:28:57.261 --> 00:28:57.760
Right?

00:28:57.760 --> 00:28:59.750
I'm either on this diet
and I'm white knuckling

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:02.660
my way through it, or I'm
face first in a box of donuts.

00:29:02.660 --> 00:29:05.020
And so I start from
the very beginning,

00:29:05.020 --> 00:29:08.030
from your elimination period
with the Whole30 saying,

00:29:08.030 --> 00:29:11.020
you're not eliminating these
foods because they're bad.

00:29:11.020 --> 00:29:12.470
They're just unknown.

00:29:12.470 --> 00:29:14.720
And you just want to figure
out how they work for you.

00:29:14.720 --> 00:29:17.290
And it's not the Whole365.

00:29:17.290 --> 00:29:18.270
It's the Whole30.

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:23.060
So it's a 30-day, scientific
elimination period.

00:29:23.060 --> 00:29:27.450
And then after that, I want you
to live in your food freedom.

00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:29.800
I want you to figure out what
does work for you and what

00:29:29.800 --> 00:29:30.300
doesn't.

00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:33.050
In fact, the goal I propose in
"Food Freedom Forever" is this.

00:29:33.050 --> 00:29:38.220
I want your diet to be as
broad an expansive as possible,

00:29:38.220 --> 00:29:40.420
while still looking
and feeling as awesome

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:41.890
as you want to look and feel.

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:43.480
And you get to draw that line.

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:45.010
I'm not drawing it for you.

00:29:45.010 --> 00:29:47.680
So I have figured out
that I can get away

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:49.210
with a couple
glasses of wine here

00:29:49.210 --> 00:29:51.520
and there, some Justin's
Peanut Butter Cups here

00:29:51.520 --> 00:29:54.160
and there, my mom's
chocolate chip walnut cake.

00:29:54.160 --> 00:29:55.916
And I still look
just as awesome.

00:29:55.916 --> 00:29:57.290
And I still feel
just as awesome.

00:29:57.290 --> 00:29:58.200
So guess what?

00:29:58.200 --> 00:30:00.890
I do because it makes
my life so delicious

00:30:00.890 --> 00:30:03.780
and healthy and rewarding
and happy, like emotionally

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:04.660
healthy.

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:06.500
So I want you to do that.

00:30:06.500 --> 00:30:08.310
And if you start
from the beginning

00:30:08.310 --> 00:30:10.185
not thinking about
these foods as bad

00:30:10.185 --> 00:30:11.810
and that's why you're
eliminating them,

00:30:11.810 --> 00:30:13.810
then you shouldn't
feel the same guilt

00:30:13.810 --> 00:30:15.430
when you bring them back in.

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:18.390
I don't want you to feel guilty
reintroducing these foods.

00:30:18.390 --> 00:30:20.390
You may make the wrong
choice sometimes.

00:30:20.390 --> 00:30:23.040
I may overdo it on the wine or
my mom's chocolate chip walnut

00:30:23.040 --> 00:30:23.540
cake.

00:30:23.540 --> 00:30:25.400
And I'm like, wow, that
was a poor decision.

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:26.390
I don't feel as good.

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:27.380
And my energy is down.

00:30:27.380 --> 00:30:28.110
My mood is down.

00:30:28.110 --> 00:30:31.170
OK, so I learned from that,
and I apply it the next time

00:30:31.170 --> 00:30:32.860
that situation comes up.

00:30:32.860 --> 00:30:36.950
But I encourage everyone
to find that line.

00:30:36.950 --> 00:30:38.900
How much can you
get away with so

00:30:38.900 --> 00:30:41.850
that your life is amazing and
rewarding and delicious and

00:30:41.850 --> 00:30:45.720
satisfying and full of your
family and friend traditions

00:30:45.720 --> 00:30:47.970
while still maintaining
all of the health

00:30:47.970 --> 00:30:50.737
benefits you want to maintain?

00:30:50.737 --> 00:30:51.570
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:53.412
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah, thanks.

00:30:53.412 --> 00:30:55.620
STACEY SASAKI: Just to follow
up on that, what if you

00:30:55.620 --> 00:30:58.990
do you overdo it and
just completely fall off

00:30:58.990 --> 00:31:00.710
after you've done your Whole30?

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:02.350
MELISSA HARTWIG:
So one of the steps

00:31:02.350 --> 00:31:06.510
in "Food Freedom Forever,"
so it's you do your reset.

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:08.180
You live your food freedom.

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:10.370
And you acknowledge that
your habits have slipped.

00:31:10.370 --> 00:31:13.110
So I have built
right into the plan

00:31:13.110 --> 00:31:15.330
that you will fall
off the wagon.

00:31:15.330 --> 00:31:16.340
Isn't that relieving?

00:31:16.340 --> 00:31:17.700
Because all of these
diets are like,

00:31:17.700 --> 00:31:19.366
oh, you're going to
do our 21-day detox,

00:31:19.366 --> 00:31:22.019
and then you'll never, ever
have to diet ever again.

00:31:22.019 --> 00:31:23.810
Everything's going to
be magically changed.

00:31:23.810 --> 00:31:25.700
And that's completely
unrealistic,

00:31:25.700 --> 00:31:27.660
even for a program as
good as the Whole30.

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:30.560
And it's good in
changing people's habits.

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:33.370
Eventually, you fall
back into old ruts.

00:31:33.370 --> 00:31:34.980
You're trying to
overwrite decades

00:31:34.980 --> 00:31:37.010
of less healthy behaviors
and associations

00:31:37.010 --> 00:31:38.610
and emotional
relationships with food.

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:40.720
You're not going to
fix that in 30 days.

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:44.120
So if that happens, you just
come back to your reset,

00:31:44.120 --> 00:31:48.110
whether it's a full Whole30,
or maybe a Whole3 or a Whole7.

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:51.750
However long you need
to feel back in control

00:31:51.750 --> 00:31:55.620
and to get that energy and
sleep and mood and digestion

00:31:55.620 --> 00:31:57.050
rocking again, cool.

00:31:57.050 --> 00:31:58.170
You know it works.

00:31:58.170 --> 00:31:59.250
You know how to do it.

00:31:59.250 --> 00:32:00.740
You know it's going to
make you feel amazing.

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:02.406
And then as soon as
you're done, as soon

00:32:02.406 --> 00:32:04.264
as you're able, as
soon as possible,

00:32:04.264 --> 00:32:06.680
because I want you to get right
back to your food freedom,

00:32:06.680 --> 00:32:09.138
you're back to living in your
normal healthy balance again.

00:32:09.138 --> 00:32:10.280
It's simple.

00:32:10.280 --> 00:32:13.000
And you continue that cycle
literally in perpetuity

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.340
until, ideally, you never need
another Whole30 ever again.

00:32:16.340 --> 00:32:18.210
I'll probably never do
a full 30 ever again.

00:32:18.210 --> 00:32:18.590
STACEY SASAKI: Really?

00:32:18.590 --> 00:32:19.720
MELISSA HARTWIG:
No, I don't need it.

00:32:19.720 --> 00:32:21.400
STACEY SASAKI: Does it
get easier each time?

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:22.030
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Of course it does.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:22.880
It gets easier.

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:23.600
You learn more.

00:32:23.600 --> 00:32:26.555
You become more selective
about what's worth it for you.

00:32:26.555 --> 00:32:29.820
You identify foods that
maybe don't work for you,

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:31.480
but it's really nuanced.

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:33.850
Oh, I didn't notice this
after my first Whole30.

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:36.610
But by my third, don't think
this is worth it anymore.

00:32:36.610 --> 00:32:37.637
Yeah, it gets easier.

00:32:37.637 --> 00:32:38.970
And it just becomes what you do.

00:32:38.970 --> 00:32:40.510
You no longer even
have to think about.

00:32:40.510 --> 00:32:41.385
STACEY SASAKI: Great.

00:32:41.385 --> 00:32:42.925
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah.

