I wrote an article called
"Business Travel 101"

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:41.930
on the whole30.com that
lays out my incredibly

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:44.255
anal retentive travel plan
because I travel so much.

00:37:44.255 --> 00:37:45.880
And it's really
important to me to make

00:37:45.880 --> 00:37:48.340
it as stress-free as possible.

00:37:48.340 --> 00:37:52.730
As for my journey, I was not
always a really healthy person.

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:54.460
I'm actually a
recovering drug addict.

00:37:54.460 --> 00:37:56.850
I've been clean for
almost 17 years.

00:37:56.850 --> 00:37:57.590
And that--

00:37:57.590 --> 00:37:58.570
[APPLAUSE]

00:37:58.570 --> 00:37:59.512
Oh, thanks.

00:37:59.512 --> 00:38:01.680
I always feel weird when
people clap for that.

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:03.220
I'm like, I got
myself messed up,

00:38:03.220 --> 00:38:05.636
so I'm not sure you should
applaud me getting unmessed up.

00:38:05.636 --> 00:38:07.350
But it is a big deal.

00:38:07.350 --> 00:38:11.506
And I started in health
and exercise and nutrition

00:38:11.506 --> 00:38:12.880
when I got out of
rehab because I

00:38:12.880 --> 00:38:14.870
knew that I had to
change everything

00:38:14.870 --> 00:38:16.110
about my life to stay clean.

00:38:16.110 --> 00:38:18.030
I had to adopt
that growth mindset

00:38:18.030 --> 00:38:19.980
and convince myself
that I wasn't

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:24.190
some degenerate, worthless loser
who couldn't change her life.

00:38:24.190 --> 00:38:25.770
So I started exercising.

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:27.130
And I started eating healthier.

00:38:27.130 --> 00:38:29.230
And I got some fitness
certifications,

00:38:29.230 --> 00:38:31.240
and ran a CrossFit
gym for a while,

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:32.710
and did some
kettlebell coaching.

00:38:32.710 --> 00:38:35.240
And that was really
where my path

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:37.980
started was through
my own transformation.

00:38:37.980 --> 00:38:39.950
And so if you've
done the Whole30,

00:38:39.950 --> 00:38:41.690
knowing this about
my background,

00:38:41.690 --> 00:38:42.990
the rules kind of make sense.

00:38:42.990 --> 00:38:44.470
The rigidity kind
of makes sense.

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:47.270
The steps and the
community makes sense

00:38:47.270 --> 00:38:51.210
because it was all of the things
that I needed to get and stay

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:52.800
clean 17 years ago.

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:54.790
So yeah, there's
a chapter on that

00:38:54.790 --> 00:38:57.800
here because if you looked at
me now, I think a lot of people

00:38:57.800 --> 00:39:00.517
would say like, what do
you know about feeling out

00:39:00.517 --> 00:39:01.600
of control with your food.

00:39:01.600 --> 00:39:02.724
I've never been overweight.

00:39:02.724 --> 00:39:04.750
That's not a struggle
or a battle I've fought.

00:39:04.750 --> 00:39:07.270
But trust me when I say
I have fought my battles.

00:39:07.270 --> 00:39:09.520
And drugs and food are not
that different in terms

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:13.430
of the impact they have on the
brain and cravings and reward

00:39:13.430 --> 00:39:16.060
and your social interactions
and your self-confidence.

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:19.240
And so I do write about that.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:20.490
Thanks.

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:24.500
STACEY SASAKI: To follow
up quickly on the food,

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:28.310
going out to eat, vacations,
that sort of thing--

00:39:28.310 --> 00:39:31.850
I think one of the great things
about Google-- there's many--

00:39:31.850 --> 00:39:33.640
is that we get a menu every day.

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:36.390
And we see all of the things
that are available to us.

00:39:36.390 --> 00:39:38.490
And it gives you all
of the allergens.

00:39:38.490 --> 00:39:40.698
But when you go to a
restaurant, you don't have that.

00:39:40.698 --> 00:39:44.234
So people who are not in this
world, how do you navigate?

00:39:44.234 --> 00:39:44.900
What do you say?

00:39:44.900 --> 00:39:45.980
How do you go out for dinner?

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:48.063
MELISSA HARTWIG: Yeah,
this is totally my process.

00:39:48.063 --> 00:39:49.940
The first thing I
do is go on Yelp.

00:39:49.940 --> 00:39:52.860
And I do a search for American
New, or grass-fed burger,

00:39:52.860 --> 00:39:55.410
or vegetarian breakfast
because for some reason,

00:39:55.410 --> 00:39:57.470
the vegetarian breakfasts
tend to lead me

00:39:57.470 --> 00:40:00.600
to the grass-fed, organic,
farm-to-table places.

00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:01.690
I look at the menu.

00:40:01.690 --> 00:40:03.130
If the menu looks
pretty doable--

00:40:03.130 --> 00:40:04.810
I'm looking for simple
protein options.

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:08.800
So it's like a steak or grilled
fish or eggs or a burger,

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:09.740
like cool.

00:40:09.740 --> 00:40:10.630
I look at the sides.

00:40:10.630 --> 00:40:12.140
Do I have a bunch
of veggie choices.

00:40:12.140 --> 00:40:13.350
Like great.

00:40:13.350 --> 00:40:15.664
Occasionally, if I have to,
I'll call the restaurant

00:40:15.664 --> 00:40:16.830
ahead of time and say, look.

00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:18.740
I'm walking in like,
this is my stuff.

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:20.340
And I don't make a
big deal out of it.

00:40:20.340 --> 00:40:22.804
I don't eat this, this,
or this right now.

00:40:22.804 --> 00:40:24.720
Do you have options that
would accommodate me?

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:27.130
Or when I come in, can
I make a some requests?

00:40:27.130 --> 00:40:31.020
I had a lamb burger at the
Breslin last night, so good.

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:32.740
But they don't do substitutions.

00:40:32.740 --> 00:40:34.700
That's very helpful
to know up front.

00:40:34.700 --> 00:40:35.680
So I walked in.

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:37.710
And I did no bun and no cheese.

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:38.480
And they did that.

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:39.980
But they wouldn't
substitute my salad

00:40:39.980 --> 00:40:41.354
dressing for a
different dressing

00:40:41.354 --> 00:40:42.640
because it was cream-based.

00:40:42.640 --> 00:40:45.122
So I just asked for lemon and
a little bit of olive oil.

00:40:45.122 --> 00:40:46.330
And they were cool with that.

00:40:46.330 --> 00:40:48.185
But it's good to
know ahead of time.

00:40:48.185 --> 00:40:49.810
So just do your
research ahead of time.

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:52.710
And then when you get
there, make your order

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:55.190
and be as matter of fact
and polite as possible.

00:40:55.190 --> 00:40:57.009
The bigger a deal
you make about it,

00:40:57.009 --> 00:40:59.050
the bigger a deal everyone
else is going to make.

00:40:59.050 --> 00:41:01.630
So don't walk in there and be
like, oh, I know it's so weird.

00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:03.070
And I'm going to be
your special person.

00:41:03.070 --> 00:41:03.860
And I'm so sorry.

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:05.442
Like no, can I have this?

00:41:05.442 --> 00:41:07.400
And can I not have the
bun and not have cheese?

00:41:07.400 --> 00:41:09.085
And can you sub the fries?

00:41:09.085 --> 00:41:10.710
I see you've got
broccoli in this dish.

00:41:10.710 --> 00:41:12.700
Can I just get some broccoli
steamed on the side?

00:41:12.700 --> 00:41:13.500
Thank you so much.

00:41:13.500 --> 00:41:15.968
And then you tip
very generously.

00:41:15.968 --> 00:41:17.461
STACEY SASAKI: I like it.

00:41:17.461 --> 00:41:19.460
AUDIENCE: That was actually
one of my questions.

00:41:19.460 --> 00:41:22.040
But the other question is,
how do you find the right time

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:23.872
to do this because I
always feel like I'm

00:41:23.872 --> 00:41:24.830
oh, I can't this month.

00:41:24.830 --> 00:41:25.871
I have two client events.

00:41:25.871 --> 00:41:27.950
Or I can't next month,
it's Thanksgiving.

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:30.530
How do you find or prioritize
the right 30 days to start?

00:41:30.530 --> 00:41:32.530
MELISSA HARTWIG: That's
a really great question.

00:41:32.530 --> 00:41:34.290
So first of all,
you want to remember

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:36.010
that it's not just the 30 days.

00:41:36.010 --> 00:41:37.599
It's 30 days plus
re-introduction.

00:41:37.599 --> 00:41:39.390
So I see people sometimes
who are like, oh,

00:41:39.390 --> 00:41:41.399
my day 31 is my trip to Italy.

00:41:41.399 --> 00:41:42.940
And I'm like, oh,
you're really going

00:41:42.940 --> 00:41:44.800
to have a hard time
reintroducing there.

00:41:44.800 --> 00:41:46.300
And if you don't
reintroduce, you're

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:48.240
missing a lot of the
benefit of the program.

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:51.160
So ideally, you're
finding a 40-day block.

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:55.590
I want you to not do the Whole30
ideally over the holidays.

00:41:55.590 --> 00:41:56.090
Right?

00:41:56.090 --> 00:41:57.701
That's just asking for trouble.

00:41:57.701 --> 00:41:59.200
Plus during the
holidays, you've got

00:41:59.200 --> 00:42:02.800
a lot of these once-a-year,
really special family foods.

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:05.630
And I don't necessarily want
you to miss out on that.

00:42:05.630 --> 00:42:09.330
So find a 40-day block where
you don't have an A level race,

00:42:09.330 --> 00:42:11.130
or you're not getting
married that month,

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:14.420
or you don't have a once in a
lifetime vacation to Croatia.

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:16.700
But a client event is
not a good enough reason.

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:18.360
I want you to
figure out how to do

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:21.830
this in all of life's
circumstances-- bridal showers,

00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:25.420
family dinners, clients
events, business lunches.

00:42:25.420 --> 00:42:28.020
You need to figure out
how to live in your food

00:42:28.020 --> 00:42:30.550
freedom, which may or may
not include these food going

00:42:30.550 --> 00:42:31.530
forward.

00:42:31.530 --> 00:42:33.960
So don't schedule
around-- you'll

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:36.530
never find 40 days where
the only thing you're doing

00:42:36.530 --> 00:42:38.160
is staying at home
watching Netflix.

00:42:38.160 --> 00:42:39.590
That's not going to happen.

00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:41.789
So make sure it's nothing
that's so special you

00:42:41.789 --> 00:42:42.830
wouldn't want to miss it.

00:42:42.830 --> 00:42:47.000
But I would include
some of those every day,

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.049
but still specialish
occurrences.

00:42:49.049 --> 00:42:50.715
And then figure out
how to make it work.

00:42:50.715 --> 00:42:51.290
Right?

00:42:51.290 --> 00:42:54.826
You're ordering a
sparkling water with lime.

00:42:54.826 --> 00:42:57.200
And you're just as festive,
and you're just as cheersing.

00:42:57.200 --> 00:43:00.754
And it's just as
happy in that hour.

00:43:00.754 --> 00:43:01.254
Yeah.

00:43:08.159 --> 00:43:08.700
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:08.700 --> 00:43:09.440
Thanks for coming.

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:10.300
MELISSA HARTWIG:
Yeah, thank you.

00:43:10.300 --> 00:43:12.640
AUDIENCE: 3 and 1/2 years
and counting and loving

00:43:12.640 --> 00:43:14.155
it, loving every minute of it.

00:43:14.155 --> 00:43:14.580
MELISSA HARTWIG: Cool.

00:43:14.580 --> 00:43:16.038
AUDIENCE: I have
one situation that

00:43:16.038 --> 00:43:19.580
continues to be challenging,
which is at this point,

00:43:19.580 --> 00:43:22.870
pretty much everyone in my life
knows that I have eating habits

00:43:22.870 --> 00:43:25.000
that they might consider
quirky or bizarre

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.100
or against conventional
wisdom or whatever it is.

00:43:27.100 --> 00:43:27.790
MELISSA HARTWIG: Sure.

00:43:27.790 --> 00:43:28.790
AUDIENCE: Occasionally,
I'm a guest

00:43:28.790 --> 00:43:30.581
in someone's house,
which happened actually

00:43:30.581 --> 00:43:33.310
this weekend, where, oh,
you can eat everything.

00:43:33.310 --> 00:43:37.410
It's all gluten free and full of
honey and artificial sweeteners

00:43:37.410 --> 00:43:41.370
and rice flour and all kinds of
things that I'm not going near.

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:44.610
How do you prepare for-- well,
I know how I prepare internally.

00:43:44.610 --> 00:43:47.150
But how do you prepare
socially for those situations

00:43:47.150 --> 00:43:49.560
and handle those with
a well-meaning host who

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:51.690
is actually going against
everything that you want?

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:52.680
MELISSA HARTWIG: I
totally get that.

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:54.590
And I had that situation
at the holidays

00:43:54.590 --> 00:43:56.580
this past year
where I was served

00:43:56.580 --> 00:43:59.410
pasta full of ricotta cheese
and I was like, oh, this

00:43:59.410 --> 00:44:00.560
is going to be tough.

00:44:00.560 --> 00:44:03.260
Are you on the Whole30
during this situation?

00:44:03.260 --> 00:44:06.410
Or is this just part
of your food freedom?

00:44:06.410 --> 00:44:07.160
AUDIENCE: I'm not.

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:10.160
MELISSA HARTWIG: OK, so
you're not on the Whole30.

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:11.980
So this is one of
those situations where

00:44:11.980 --> 00:44:17.320
you have to weigh sticking to
your preferences versus really

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:18.940
hurting someone's feelings.

00:44:18.940 --> 00:44:20.810
Ideally, you're having
a conversation ahead

00:44:20.810 --> 00:44:22.235
of time, if at all possible.

00:44:22.235 --> 00:44:24.091
Hey, I just want
to let you know.

00:44:24.091 --> 00:44:26.090
Just like if you were a
vegetarian, for example.

00:44:26.090 --> 00:44:27.630
I just want to let
you know that I

00:44:27.630 --> 00:44:29.130
don't eat this, this, and this.

00:44:29.130 --> 00:44:30.640
If that's going to be a
problem with your menu,

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:31.910
I'd be happy to bring a dish.

00:44:31.910 --> 00:44:33.900
Let me know what I
could contribute.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:36.652
When you get there, if they've
gone out of the way and said,

00:44:36.652 --> 00:44:39.110
this is all gluten-free, but
it's full of this other stuff,

00:44:39.110 --> 00:44:42.210
then it comes down to, how bad
is it going to mess you up.

00:44:42.210 --> 00:44:44.140
If it's going to
seriously mess you up

00:44:44.140 --> 00:44:47.550
with migraines or
headaches or asthma

00:44:47.550 --> 00:44:49.930
or whatever, then you have
to politely decline, and say,

00:44:49.930 --> 00:44:52.190
you know what, I
really would love to.

00:44:52.190 --> 00:44:54.950
And I'm so, so thankful that you
took the time to prepare this.

00:44:54.950 --> 00:44:57.700
But I really have a bad reaction
with artificial sweeteners.

00:44:57.700 --> 00:44:59.408
And if I eat it, this
is going to happen.

00:44:59.408 --> 00:45:01.440
So I'll politely decline,
but thank you so much.

00:45:01.440 --> 00:45:05.110
If it's just a preference,
then you have to think about,

00:45:05.110 --> 00:45:06.890
I might just take
one for the team.

00:45:06.890 --> 00:45:10.960
And eat as little as
possible to be polite.

00:45:10.960 --> 00:45:12.182
Share with someone else.

00:45:12.182 --> 00:45:13.640
Pass your plate on
to someone else.

00:45:13.640 --> 00:45:15.515
Take a bite or two and
say, this was amazing.

00:45:15.515 --> 00:45:16.380
Thank you so much.

00:45:16.380 --> 00:45:17.940
But I'm saving for
the next course

00:45:17.940 --> 00:45:19.640
if you know it's more edible.

00:45:19.640 --> 00:45:21.930
But this is where
you have to weigh

00:45:21.930 --> 00:45:24.460
hurting someone's feelings and
being gracious against what

00:45:24.460 --> 00:45:28.440
is really just a preference
and not an actual sensitivity.

00:45:28.440 --> 00:45:32.420
So I ate three bites of
this pasta with ricotta.

00:45:32.420 --> 00:45:34.462
And I knew the dairy
was going to kill me.

00:45:34.462 --> 00:45:36.420
I spent the rest of the
night not feeling well.

00:45:36.420 --> 00:45:38.535
But it was the
woman I didn't know.

00:45:38.535 --> 00:45:40.410
I didn't have any
opportunity to communicate.

00:45:40.410 --> 00:45:41.380
I ate a couple bites.

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:43.050
I passed it along
and said, I'm really

00:45:43.050 --> 00:45:44.540
saving for the
next course, which

00:45:44.540 --> 00:45:46.340
I knew I could totally eat.

00:45:46.340 --> 00:45:48.250
And I sucked it up and took it.

00:45:48.250 --> 00:45:50.660
And so sometimes you
just have to decide

00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:52.480
what's worth it for you.

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:52.980
Yeah.

00:45:58.890 --> 00:46:00.570
AUDIENCE: My wife
doesn't eat eggs.

00:46:00.570 --> 00:46:04.110
And I was wondering what
kind of interesting options

00:46:04.110 --> 00:46:07.207
for breakfasts that you
do during the Whole30.

00:46:07.207 --> 00:46:08.790
MELISSA HARTWIG: I
love that question.

00:46:08.790 --> 00:46:10.360
We get that question
all the time.

00:46:10.360 --> 00:46:11.690
In fact, in the
"Whole30" book, there's

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:14.480
a whole intro about what you can
eat for breakfast if you're not

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:15.180
eating eggs.

00:46:15.180 --> 00:46:17.885
So first of all,
I really encourage

00:46:17.885 --> 00:46:20.010
people to get that idea of
breakfast, lunch, dinner

00:46:20.010 --> 00:46:20.718
out of your head.

00:46:20.718 --> 00:46:22.820
We just call them Meal
1, Meal 2, and Meal 3.

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:24.970
And for Meal 1, I'm just
as likely to have a burger

00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:26.010
as I am to have an omelet.

00:46:26.010 --> 00:46:27.551
The other morning,
I literally cooked

00:46:27.551 --> 00:46:29.850
a burger for Megan and I.
That was our breakfast.

00:46:29.850 --> 00:46:31.140
And it was amazing.

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:34.410
So you can have absolutely
anything you want,

00:46:34.410 --> 00:46:39.450
leftovers for breakfast,
or cook any kind of protein

00:46:39.450 --> 00:46:40.070
that you want.

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:42.360
But if you want more
of a breakfasty feel,

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:44.130
we do have some
really good recipes.

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:48.360
So think things like
ground chicken and apples

00:46:48.360 --> 00:46:52.020
and sweet potato and
a few diced walnuts

00:46:52.020 --> 00:46:55.640
with a little apple cider
vinegar, a warm hash style.

00:46:55.640 --> 00:46:58.820
Sausage, whether
it's pork sausage,

00:46:58.820 --> 00:47:02.550
ideally pastured and organic,
or some kind of chicken sausage

00:47:02.550 --> 00:47:04.480
would be a good choice.

00:47:04.480 --> 00:47:05.920
Soups in the morning are good.

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:07.820
I also love a good
breakfast salad,

00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:09.060
which I know sounds weird.

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:10.476
But I got into the
habit of eating

00:47:10.476 --> 00:47:13.570
salad first thing in the morning
when I was in Scandinavia,

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:15.416
and just fell in
love with the idea.

00:47:15.416 --> 00:47:17.540
So maybe breakfast salads
with some sort of protein

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:20.880
on top that just feel different,
so almost so different

00:47:20.880 --> 00:47:23.030
that it's cool that you're
eating it for breakfast.

00:47:23.030 --> 00:47:23.863
But there are a lot.

00:47:23.863 --> 00:47:26.172
If you just Google Whole30
